    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/vad-hemolysis-absolute-threshold",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD model predicts absolute hemolysis index below clinical threshold across all VAD operating conditions",
      "description": "This claim asserts that the CFD hemolysis model, applied to the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry under Class III VAD operating conditions (5 flow-speed combinations spanning 3–6 L/min at 2500–3500 RPM), predicts a normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) below the clinically accepted absolute threshold of 0.01 g/100 L at all operating points. The assessment draws on (i) a comprehensive mesh-independence study across four refinement levels, (ii) Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation over material property distributions and boundary condition variability, (iii) comparison of predicted NIH against in-vitro measurements from three independent laboratory replicates reported in the open literature, and (iv) power-law hemolysis model calibration against the Heuser–Opitz dataset. Taken together, the body of computational and experimental work is considered sufficient to support regulatory submission under ASME V&V 40 at Model Risk Level 5. The claim scope is restricted to the specific pump geometry, blood analogue fluid properties, and steady-state operating envelope evaluated; extrapolation to pulsatile flow or alternative geometries is explicitly excluded."
    }
  ],
